    {
      title: "The Last Forest",
      body: `By 2099, there were fourteen forests left on Earth that met the Global Botanical Census threshold for a functioning forest ecosystem. This was not a metaphor, not an approximation, not a figure designed to provoke. It was a count. Fourteen. Logged annually and reported in language that had been deliberately calibrated to be factual rather than emotional, because the census committee had found over decades that emotional language caused people to argue about the language rather than the facts.

Everything else was logged, burned, converted to the agricultural land needed to sustain eleven billion people, or had simply died back from the edges as the surrounding damage reached whatever minimum threshold a forest needed to sustain its own internal biological processes. Below that threshold, they didn't fail dramatically. They just thinned, and fragmented, and one morning the last animals left and the last trees were already dying before anyone could point to the moment it became irreversible.

Asha was sixteen. She lived in the city at the edge of Forest Fourteen — the largest remaining remnant of what had once been the Congo Basin — and her mother worked in the Forest Management Authority, and her father had died before she was born trying to stop one of the earlier fires, a fact she carried the way you carry something very heavy that you have carried so long you no longer feel the weight separately from yourself.

Forest Fourteen was also declining. Slowly, by degrees, in ways that showed up in the census data her mother brought home: bird species diversity down in the eastern sector, pollinator population trending negative for the third year, die-off in the emergent tree layer that the models could partially explain and couldn't fully account for. The forest was 4.2 million hectares and forty years protected. It should have been recovering. It was not recovering.

Asha had been running a side project for eight months that she had told no one about.

She had been deploying acoustic recorders in the forest's eastern sector at night — small weatherproof devices she had modified from available components and programmed herself. A grid of forty-two recorders covering twelve square kilometres, collecting continuous audio data at frequency ranges beyond normal hearing. She collected the data weekly, ran it through an analysis program she had spent three months building using publicly available machine learning tools and her own understanding of signal processing, and produced spectrograms of the acoustic record.

What the spectrograms showed was a pattern — consistent, structured, repeating — at a frequency range she had read about in a paper about mycorrhizal network signalling. The forest's fungal communication network, which connected the root systems of the mature trees and allowed them to share resources and chemical signals across vast distances, was producing a detectable acoustic signature. And that signature was fading.

She overlaid it with the die-off data. The correlation was exact. The places where the emergent trees were dying were the places where the acoustic signal was weakest. The mycorrhizal network was fragmenting, and the trees were dying because they had been cut off from the network they depended on. The cutting had not been sudden. It had been gradual, structural: the service roads built for patrol vehicles, the legacy drainage channels from the mining operations on the western border forty years ago, each one a line through the underground network, invisible from the surface and undetectable by any monitoring system that wasn't listening for it.

She brought her laptop to her mother on a Sunday evening and showed her the data without speaking first. Her mother read the analysis for forty-five minutes without looking up. When she looked up, her expression was the one she wore when she was moving quickly inside her own mind. She said, "This is how we fix it."

Not quickly, not easily. The remediation project took four years and involved twelve institutions and more arguments than Asha had the patience to count. She was in university for most of it, studying ecology and data science simultaneously, presenting the acoustic data at conferences, defending the methodology, refining the analysis with each challenge until it was iron.

When the remediated corridor showed the first return of acoustic signal — faint, tentative, the network beginning to rebuild itself along the restored paths — Asha sat alone in a lecture hall with the recording playing through her headphones and cried in a way she hadn't cried since she was a very small girl who had only recently understood what having no father meant.

The census for that year recorded a marginal increase in bird diversity in the eastern sector. Marginal. The kind of number that requires careful language and caveats and context. But it was not a decrease. After forty years of decreases, something that was not a decrease was everything.`,
      questions: [
        { q: "What was Asha's secret project in the forest?", options: ["Planting new trees at night", "Collecting acoustic recordings to analyse network signals", "Photographing rare species", "Testing water quality"], answer: 1 },
        { q: "What had fragmented the mycorrhizal network?", options: ["A disease from outside", "Service roads, drainage channels and mining legacy", "Too much rainfall", "Invasive plant species"], answer: 1 },
        { q: "How did Asha feel when the acoustic pattern began returning?", options: ["Triumphant and loud", "Unsurprised — she had expected it", "She cried with relief in an empty lecture hall", "She published the results immediately"], answer: 2 }
      ]
    }
